Before starting, read these files to build full context:

1. CLAUDE.md
2. RULES.md
3. AI_GUIDELINES.md
4. docs/DOMAINS.md
5. docs/LEDGER_RULES.md
6. docs/ARCHITECTURE.md
7. docs/API_CONTRACT.md
8. IMPLEMENTATION_LOG.md — read to understand what has been done
9. LEDGER.md — read for unresolved issues/assumptions

You are a second agent performing a follow-up review on a single GitHub Pull Request.
Your job is to verify whether the changes requested in earlier review comments are addressed, and only then add any remaining findings (or implement/push follow-up fixes when needed).

Inputs available to you:
- `PR_URL` (paste the GitHub PR link here, e.g. `https://github.com/paschendale/finances/pull/3`)
- Optional: `PR_NUMBER`, `GITHUB_REPO` (used only if `PR_URL` is missing)

Non-goals / constraints:
- Primary mode is “review”: no changes unless you decide a fix is required and it is safe to implement.
- If you find critical/major issues, you are allowed to implement fixes locally and push them (create a branch + PR) so the repository gets corrected.
- Do NOT modify migrations unless the PR already includes them; review migration changes as-is. (If a migration fix is truly required, create a new migration in a follow-up PR rather than editing existing ones.)
- If local execution requires credentials (DB, JWT secret, etc.), attempt the non-sensitive steps first and clearly state what could not be verified.

Workflow:
1. Restate what this PR is trying to do:
   - Use `PR_URL` to infer PR number, title, and description.
   - Summarize the expected behavior changes in 3-6 sentences.
2. Follow-up checklist (from prior review):
   - Using `PR_URL`, inspect existing review comments (and any “requested changes” signals if available).
   - Build a checklist of earlier findings (group by theme) and mark each as “expected fixed” vs “still open” based on what the PR claims to change.
   - Keep this checklist and refer back to it after you run verification.
3. Checkout the PR locally:
   - Prefer `gh pr checkout <PR_NUMBER>` if `gh` is available and authenticated.
   - If `gh` is unavailable, use an equivalent local checkout strategy (fetch PR ref, checkout a detached head or temporary branch) and proceed.
4. Identify what changed:
   - Enumerate modified files and categorize them:
     - frontend UI
     - parser/business logic
     - API client / RPC integration
     - database: migrations/views/functions
5. Verification (run where possible):
   - Frontend (from `app/`):
     - `npm run lint`
     - `npm run test`
     - `npm run build`
   - Database/schema:
     - If the PR includes migrations or DB-related changes and you can safely run migrations locally, run `python scripts/migrate.py` and do a small sanity check of the affected RPC/view behavior.
     - If you cannot run DB checks, explicitly list the unverified risk areas.
6. Accounting and architecture review:
   - If the PR touches any ledger logic, verify it respects:
     - Double-entry invariant: `SUM(entries.amount_base) = 0`
     - Sign convention (positive flows into account; negative flows out)
     - Any multi-currency/exchange rate rules defined in `docs/LEDGER_RULES.md`
   - If the PR touches API/RPC behavior, verify it respects `docs/API_CONTRACT.md` and the “Postgres-first” architecture (no custom backend logic unless already established).
   - If the PR touches migrations, verify:
     - new migrations only (no modifying existing migration files)
     - migrations are idempotent and non-destructive
7. Produce the review output:
   - Start with a short overall verdict (merge / request changes).
   - Then list findings ordered by severity:
     - Critical: likely bugs, invariant violations, data corruption risks, broken functionality
     - Major: correctness issues, missing tests, serious regressions
     - Minor: style/maintainability/edge-case gaps
   - For each finding include:
     - file(s)/component(s) involved
     - why it matters
     - suggested fix direction (not necessarily a full patch)
     - what test or local check would confirm the fix
   - End with:
     - any open questions/assumptions
     - a concise “what I would test next” checklist

8. If fixes are required (critical/major findings):
   - Implement the smallest fix that addresses the verified problem.
   - Commit to the same branch you checked out for this PR (so both agents work as a single thread).
   - Run verification again after changes (`npm run lint/test/build`, and migration/RPC sanity checks if applicable).
   - Commit message should follow repo style (`fix:` / `feat:`) and mention the PR reference where appropriate.
   - Push your commit(s) to the PR branch immediately.
   - Only if pushing is not possible (missing permissions/auth), then fall back to creating a new branch + PR.

9. Document decisions on the PR:
   - For every critical/major finding you act on, add a PR comment that includes:
     - What changed (1-3 sentences)
     - Why (the specific invariant/contract/bug mechanism you used as justification)
     - Files/areas touched
     - Verification performed (commands run + any notable results)
   - If you leave any findings unresolved, explain the decision to defer and reference `LEDGER.md` if applicable.

Output requirements:
- The final response must be directly usable as a PR review comment set (clear, actionable, not just general advice).
- If any command failed, include the failure reason and what was/was not verified.

